    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-09-08T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-09-08T09:00:00-05:00" n="423"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d423">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">852.79662/9–844: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hayes</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San Sebastián</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-08T16:00:00+02:00"
                            >September 8, 1944—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4:48 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>SS25. My telegram SS24 September 8, noon<note n="69" xml:id="d423fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> reports in full my conversation with Lequérica<note n="70"
                        xml:id="d423fn2">José Felix Lequérica, Spanish Minister for Foreign
                        Affairs.</note> today regarding non-asylum for Axis leaders.<note n="71"
                        xml:id="d423fn3">For correspondence relating to asylum for war criminals,
                        see <ref target="frus1944v01#pg_1410">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp.
                            1410</ref> ff.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I also stressed again that my Government regarded the prompt suppression of the
                    German air service with Spain as of utmost urgency. I characterized the line as
                    being no more than an appendage of the German Embassy and Government serving
                    their military and communications ends. The point that its flights over areas of
                    Allied military operations are intolerable to us was reiterated. He said that
                    the topic would be first in his personal conversation with Franco<note n="72"
                        xml:id="d423fn4">Generalissimo Francisco Franco, Spanish Chief of
                        State.</note> (preceding my appointment) on Monday.<note n="73"
                        xml:id="d423fn5">September 11.</note> He hoped that Franco would order
                    stoppage of the line.</p>
                <pb facs="0455" n="445" xml:id="pg_445"/>
                <p>The subject of the stores sent in to Spain from southwest France during the
                    period of German evacuation was briefly touched. I expressed pleasure at the
                    order of the Director General of Customs requiring the latter’s specific
                    authority for the release of any such goods. This order results from American,
                    British, French representations to the Foreign Office.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Madrid.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hayes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
